07300nam a22009375i 9780226574615DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20202019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019016543  a9780226574615  a(DE-B1597)545016  a(OCoLC)1143831412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aLB2806.24b.S73 2019 4aLB2806.24b.S73 2019 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a378.7322300aProductivity in Higher Education /ced. by Kevin Stange, Caroline M. Hoxby. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b96 line drawings, 72 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. What Health Care Teaches Us about Measuring Productivity in Higher Education -- t2. The Productivity of US Postsecondary Institutions -- t3. Labor Market Outcomes and Postsecondary Accountability: Are Imperfect Metrics Better Than None? -- t4. Learning and Earning: An Approximation to College Value Added in Two Dimensions -- t5. The Costs of and Net Returns to College Major -- t6. Faculty Deployment in Research Universities -- t7. Measuring Instructor Effectiveness in Higher Education -- t8. The Competitive Effects of Online Education -- t9. Estimating the Productivity of Community Colleges in Paving the Road to Four- Year College Success -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do the benefits of higher education compare with its costs, and how does this comparison vary across individuals and institutions? These questions are fundamental to quantifying the productivity of the education sector. The studies in Productivity in Higher Education use rich and novel administrative data, modern econometric methods, and careful institutional analysis to explore productivity issues. The authors examine the returns to undergraduate education, differences in costs by major, the productivity of for-profit schools, the productivity of various types of faculty and of outcomes, the effects of online education on the higher education market, and the ways in which the productivity of different institutions responds to market forces. The analyses recognize five key challenges to assessing productivity in higher education: the potential for multiple student outcomes in terms of skills, earnings, invention, and employment; the fact that colleges and universities are “multiproduct” firms that conduct varied activities across many domains; the fact that students select which school to attend based in part on their aptitude; the difficulty of attributing outcomes to individual institutions when students attend more than one; and the possibility that some of the benefits of higher education may arise from the system as a whole rather than from a single institution. The findings and the approaches illustrated can facilitate decision-making processes in higher education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxCosts. 0aEducational accountabilityzUnited States. 0aEducational productivityzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aearnings outcomes.  ahigher education.  ainvestment.  aproductivity.  apublic benefits.  aresource allocation.1 aAltonji, Joseph G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrell, Scott E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourant, Paul N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeming, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoxby, Caroline M., econtributor.4c